00:38:08.466 --> 00:38:11.191
English translation for Yahweh,
the proper name,

00:38:11.191 --> 00:38:13.510
like almost a personal name for
God.

00:38:13.510 --> 00:38:17.380
And then in other places we
have this word Elohim,

00:38:17.380 --> 00:38:21.526
which actually is the word for
"gods," a sort of generic term

00:38:21.526 --> 00:38:23.599
for deities in the plural.
 

00:38:23.599 --> 00:38:25.906
However, when it's used to
refer to the God of Israel it's

00:38:25.906 --> 00:38:27.929
clearly singular,
it always has a singular verb.

00:38:27.929 --> 00:38:32.153
So that will be appearing in
your text as "God" with a

00:38:32.153 --> 00:38:34.941
capital G.
So whenever you see "Lord" or

00:38:34.941 --> 00:38:38.478
"God" those are actually
pointing to different words that

00:38:38.478 --> 00:38:41.510
are being used in the underlying
Hebrew text.

00:38:41.510 --> 00:38:44.179
Twice God is said to look down
on creation.

00:38:44.179 --> 00:38:46.409
Twice it is said that he is
displeased.

00:38:46.409 --> 00:38:49.039
Twice he decides to destroy all
living things.

00:38:49.039 --> 00:38:51.951
Twice he issues instructions
and as we've seen they're

00:38:51.951 --> 00:38:53.895
contradictory.
We seem to also have a

00:38:53.895 --> 00:38:56.219
different account of how long
the flood lasted;

00:38:56.219 --> 00:38:58.941
there are more subtle
contradictions throughout as

00:38:58.941 --> 00:39:01.312
well.
Sometimes the flood seems to be

00:39:01.312 --> 00:39:05.020
the result of very heavy rain,
but in other descriptions it

00:39:05.020 --> 00:39:07.449
seems to be a real cosmic
upheaval.

00:39:07.449 --> 00:39:10.773
You'll remember the description
of the world from Genesis 1 as

00:39:10.773 --> 00:39:13.988
an air bubble essentially that's
formed by separating waters

00:39:13.988 --> 00:39:15.460
above and waters below.
 

00:39:15.460 --> 00:39:18.710
They're held back or pressed
back by the firmament above.

00:39:18.710 --> 00:39:21.015
And it's the windows in the
firmament that are opened--those

00:39:21.015 --> 00:39:23.400
waters are allowed to rush in
and dissolve that air bubble.

00:39:23.400 --> 00:39:26.236
It's as if we're back to square
one with the deep,

00:39:26.236 --> 00:39:27.940
right?
Just this watery mass again.

00:39:27.940 --> 00:39:31.674
So it's creation undoing itself
in some of the descriptions,

00:39:31.674 --> 00:39:33.699
as opposed to just heavy rain.
 

00:39:33.699 --> 00:39:36.909
And in keeping with that idea
of a kind of a return to chaos,

00:39:36.909 --> 00:39:40.440
Noah is represented in a way as
the beginning of a new creation.

00:39:40.440 --> 00:39:43.239
Because like Adam and Eve in
the first creation story,

00:39:43.239 --> 00:39:45.510
Noah is told to be fruitful and
multiply.

00:39:45.510 --> 00:39:48.598
He's also given rule over
everything, and that's now

00:39:48.598 --> 00:39:51.019
extended to the taking of human
life .

00:39:51.019 --> 00:39:55.860
The Bible contains a lot of
repetition and contradiction.

00:39:55.860 --> 00:39:59.596
And sometimes it occurs in one
passage, as in the flood story

00:39:59.596 --> 00:40:03.331
here, and sometimes it occurs in
stories or passages that are

00:40:03.331 --> 00:40:06.548
separate from one another,
for example,

00:40:06.548 --> 00:40:09.469
the two creation stories.
 

00:40:09.469 --> 00:40:12.237
There are many significant
differences between the two

00:40:12.237 --> 00:40:13.230
creation stories.
 

00:40:13.230 --> 00:40:15.389
They different greatly in style.
 

00:40:15.389 --> 00:40:18.397
Genesis 1 is formalized,
it's highly structured,

00:40:18.397 --> 00:40:21.659
it has the seven days and
everything's paired up.

00:40:21.659 --> 00:40:24.039
It's beautifully structured,
it's very abstract.

00:40:24.039 --> 00:40:27.349
Genesis 2 is much more
dramatic, much more earthy.

00:40:27.349 --> 00:40:30.304
The first creation story
doesn't really contain puns and

00:40:30.304 --> 00:40:32.400
wordplays, it's a little bit
serious.

00:40:32.400 --> 00:40:34.272
The second creation story is
full of them:

00:40:34.272 --> 00:40:37.150
there are all sorts of little
ironies and puns in the Hebrew.

00:40:37.150 --> 00:40:39.083
Adam,
the earthling made from the

00:40:39.083 --> 00:40:40.624
earth.
Adam is made from

00:40:40.624 --> 00:40:42.541
adamah.
Adam and Eve are naked,

00:40:42.541 --> 00:40:44.525
arum,
which is the same word for

00:40:44.525 --> 00:40:46.897
clever or shrewd,
and the snake is arum,

00:40:46.897 --> 00:40:49.277
he's clever and shrewd:
there are lots of little puns

00:40:49.277 --> 00:40:51.394
of this kind.
There are also differences in

00:40:51.394 --> 00:40:53.159
terminology between the two
stories.

00:40:53.159 --> 00:40:57.858
Genesis 1 speaks of male and
female, one set of Hebrew terms,

00:40:57.858 --> 00:41:00.599
but Genesis 2 uses man and
woman,

00:41:00.599 --> 00:41:03.170
a different set of Hebrew terms
to describe the genders.

00:41:03.170 --> 00:41:06.760
So the terms for gender are
different in the two stories.

00:41:06.760 --> 00:41:10.876
Genesis 1 refers to God,
as in your translation "God,"

00:41:10.876 --> 00:41:14.450
Elohim, the word that's
translated as "God."

00:41:14.450 --> 00:41:16.599
He's remote, he's transcendent.
 

00:41:16.599 --> 00:41:21.019
He creates effortlessly through
his word and through his will.

00:41:21.019 --> 00:41:24.337
But Genesis 2 refers to the
deity as a name that's really a

00:41:24.337 --> 00:41:27.597
combination, it's Yahweh Elohim,
so you'll see '"Lord God"

00:41:27.597 --> 00:41:29.403
right?
You see that a lot in the Bible

00:41:29.403 --> 00:41:30.159
as well, Lord God.
 

00:41:30.159 --> 00:41:32.159
That tells you both of those
words were side by side in the

00:41:32.159 --> 00:41:34.687
original Hebrew.
So in Genesis 2 the deity is

00:41:34.687 --> 00:41:37.239
Yahweh Elohim.
He's much more down to earth.

00:41:37.239 --> 00:41:39.869
He forms the human like a
potter working with clay.

00:41:39.869 --> 00:41:41.898
He talks to himself,
he plants a garden,

00:41:41.898 --> 00:41:45.070
he takes a stroll in the garden
in the cool of the evening.

00:41:45.070 --> 00:41:48.150
He makes clothes for Adam and
Eve.

00:41:48.150 --> 00:41:51.721
He's spoken of in much more
anthropomorphic terms then the

00:41:51.721 --> 00:41:54.039
God that we encounter in Genesis
1.

00:41:54.039 --> 00:41:57.398
So what we have in the first
few chapters of Genesis are two

00:41:57.398 --> 00:42:00.130
creation stories that have
distinctive styles,

00:42:00.130 --> 00:42:03.004
distinctive themes,
distinctive vocabularies and

00:42:03.004 --> 00:42:04.840
they're placed side by side.
 

00:42:04.840 --> 00:42:08.440
In Genesis 6 through 9 we seem
to have two flood stories with

00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:11.505
distinctive styles,
and themes, and vocabularies,

00:42:11.505 --> 00:42:14.867
and substantive details,
but they're interwoven instead

00:42:14.867 --> 00:42:16.860
of being placed side by side.
 

00:42:16.860 --> 00:42:19.869
And there are many such
doublets in the Bible.

00:42:19.869 --> 00:42:23.351
At times we have whole books
that repeat or go over the same

00:42:23.351 --> 00:42:25.859
material.
In fact the whole historical

00:42:25.859 --> 00:42:29.378
saga that's recorded from
Genesis through the end of 2

00:42:29.378 --> 00:42:33.097
Kings is rehearsed again in the
books of First and Second

00:42:33.097 --> 00:42:35.991
Chronicles.
What are we to make of the

00:42:35.991 --> 00:42:38.949
repetitions and the
contradictions here and

00:42:38.949 --> 00:42:40.640
throughout the Bible?
 

00:42:40.640 --> 00:42:42.360
What are the implications?
 

00:42:42.360 --> 00:42:46.214
Suppose you came across a piece
of writing that you knew nothing

00:42:46.214 --> 00:42:48.539
about just lying there on the
table.

00:42:48.539 --> 00:42:51.080
You didn't know who wrote it,
where, when,

00:42:51.080 --> 00:42:54.673
how, why, and someone says to
you, "I want you to draw some

00:42:54.673 --> 00:42:57.400
conclusions about that piece of
writing.

00:42:57.400 --> 00:43:00.172
I want you to draw some
conclusions about its authorship

00:43:00.172 --> 00:43:02.340
and the way it was compiled or
composed."

00:43:02.340 --> 00:43:05.387
And so you pick it up and you
start reading and you notice

00:43:05.387 --> 00:43:06.510
features like this.
 

00:43:06.510 --> 00:43:09.079
What might you conclude?
 

00:43:09.079 --> 00:43:12.100
Throw it out,
what might you conclude?

00:43:12.100 --> 00:43:13.510
No presuppositions.
 

00:43:13.510 --> 00:43:15.750
You pick up the work and you
find these features.

00:43:15.750 --> 00:43:18.750
What might you conclude about
its authorship or manner of

00:43:18.750 --> 00:43:21.511
composition?
Student: There are

00:43:21.511 --> 00:43:22.960
multiple authors.
 

00:43:22.960 --> 00:43:24.748
Professor Christine
Hayes: You might conclude

00:43:24.748 --> 00:43:25.940
that there are multiple authors.
 

00:43:25.940 --> 00:43:27.940
Right?
Multiple authorship.

00:43:27.940 --> 00:43:30.933
Yeah?
Student: There are

00:43:30.933 --> 00:43:32.732
revisions.
Professor Christine

00:43:32.732 --> 00:43:34.636
Hayes: That revisions may
have been made,

00:43:34.636 --> 00:43:36.973
so that you might have
different sources that have been

00:43:36.973 --> 00:43:38.747
revised or put together in
different ways.

00:43:38.747 --> 00:43:40.893
Right?
Revisions implying that you've

00:43:40.893 --> 00:43:43.269
got something and then it's
worked over again,

00:43:43.269 --> 00:43:46.119
additions might be made so now
that's a new source.

00:43:46.119 --> 00:43:49.243
You might conclude that these
features are evidence of

00:43:49.243 --> 00:43:52.154
multiple authorship;
a good deal of revision which

00:43:52.154 --> 00:43:54.715
points itself to a kind of
composite structure,

00:43:54.715 --> 00:43:57.219
different layers maybe,
different sources.

00:43:57.219 --> 00:44:00.260
Well as early as the Middle
Ages there were some scholars

00:44:00.260 --> 00:44:02.920
who noticed these things in the
biblical texts.

00:44:02.920 --> 00:44:05.465
They noticed that there are
contradictions and repetitions

00:44:05.465 --> 00:44:08.424
and there are anachronisms too,
other features that were

00:44:08.424 --> 00:44:11.825
evidence of multiple authorship,
revisions and composite

00:44:11.825 --> 00:44:14.781
structure.
So what?

00:44:14.781 --> 00:44:22.849
Why would that be a big deal?
 

00:44:22.849 --> 00:44:26.165
Student: [inaudible]
Professor Christine

00:44:26.165 --> 00:44:29.277
Hayes: Okay,
it could be a bit of a problem

00:44:29.277 --> 00:44:33.201
if this text has become the
basis for a system of religious

00:44:33.201 --> 00:44:36.099
faith or belief,
and your assumptions about it

00:44:36.099 --> 00:44:38.869
are that its telling a truth
that is singular in nature.

00:44:38.869 --> 00:44:41.927
And also what about the
traditional beliefs on the

00:44:41.927 --> 00:44:43.300
origin of this text?
 

00:44:43.300 --> 00:44:45.441
Right, who wrote this text
according to traditional

00:44:45.441 --> 00:44:45.870
beliefs?
 

00:44:45.870 --> 00:44:49.429
 
 

00:44:49.429 --> 00:44:50.812
I'm hearing Moses,
I'm hearing God,

00:44:50.812 --> 00:44:52.519
I'm hearing a bunch of
different things,

00:44:52.519 --> 00:44:56.400
but there are traditional ideas
about generally the Mosaic

00:44:56.400 --> 00:45:00.072
authorship of the Bible,
certainly the first five books

00:45:00.072 --> 00:45:02.385
of the Bible.
And so these features of the

00:45:02.385 --> 00:45:05.134
text which were noticed were a
challenge to traditional

00:45:05.134 --> 00:45:08.138
religious convictions regarding
the Mosaic authorship of the

00:45:08.138 --> 00:45:11.592
first five books of the Bible,
and in many ways the perfection

00:45:11.592 --> 00:45:13.696
of the Bible,
as speaking with a unified

00:45:13.696 --> 00:45:16.610
voice on matters of doctrine or
religious theology.

00:45:16.610 --> 00:45:20.378
So medieval commentators for
example began to speak a little

00:45:20.378 --> 00:45:23.380
bit more openly about some of
these features.

00:45:23.380 --> 00:45:27.121
One of the first things they
noticed is that Deuteronomy 34

00:45:27.121 --> 00:45:29.829
describes the death and burial
of Moses.

00:45:29.829 --> 00:45:33.731
So they decided it was possible
that Moses didn't write at least

00:45:33.731 --> 00:45:35.726
that chapter.
Similarly there are some

00:45:35.726 --> 00:45:37.460
anachronisms that they had to
explain.

00:45:37.460 --> 00:45:41.199
One of the most famous is in
Genesis 13:7.

00:45:41.199 --> 00:45:44.132
It's in the midst of a story
about dividing the land between

00:45:44.132 --> 00:45:46.269
Lot and--at that time his name
was Abram,

00:45:46.269 --> 00:45:48.820
it later becomes Abraham--but
between Lot and Abram.

00:45:48.820 --> 00:45:51.922
And the narrator in telling
this story sort of interjects

00:45:51.922 --> 00:45:53.639
and turns to us,
the readers,

00:45:53.639 --> 00:45:57.809
and says, "The Canaanites and
Perrizites were then dwelling in

00:45:57.809 --> 00:46:00.476
the land."
Now what's weird about that

00:46:00.476 --> 00:46:02.710
sentence?
The narrator is speaking to us

00:46:02.710 --> 00:46:05.554
from a time in which the
Canaanites and Perrizites don't

00:46:05.554 --> 00:46:06.949
live in the land,
right?

00:46:06.949 --> 00:46:11.469
"That's back when the Native
Americans lived in Connecticut."

00:46:11.469 --> 00:46:13.628
Is that writer living at a time
when Native Americans are still

00:46:13.628 --> 00:46:15.230
living in Connecticut or owning
Connecticut?

00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:16.608
No.
They're writing from a later

00:46:16.608 --> 00:46:18.642
point of view.
So the narrator breaks and

00:46:18.642 --> 00:46:20.981
talks to the audience in Genesis
13:7 and says,

00:46:20.981 --> 00:46:23.880
"That was back in the time when
the Canaanites were in the

00:46:23.880 --> 00:46:25.418
land."
When did Moses live?

00:46:25.418 --> 00:46:27.570
Who lived in the land in the
time of Moses?

00:46:27.570 --> 00:46:29.680
The Canaanites.
I know you haven't gotten there

00:46:29.680 --> 00:46:31.704
yet, but when you get to
Deuteronomy you're going to find

00:46:31.704 --> 00:46:33.150
out he doesn't make it into the
land.

00:46:33.150 --> 00:46:35.802
So he never makes it in there,
he never gets in before the

00:46:35.802 --> 00:46:36.780
Israelites conquer.
 

00:46:36.780 --> 00:46:39.150
He dies--the Canaanites are
still in possession.

00:46:39.150 --> 00:46:42.250
So that line was certainly
written not by Moses;

00:46:42.250 --> 00:46:44.907
it was written by someone at a
much later time who's looking

00:46:44.907 --> 00:46:47.654
back and referring to the time
when the Canaanites were in the

00:46:47.654 --> 00:46:49.256
land.
So these are the kinds of

00:46:49.256 --> 00:46:50.980
things that people began to
notice.

00:46:50.980 --> 00:46:53.453
And with the rise of
rationalism in the modern

00:46:53.453 --> 00:46:56.860
period, traditional notions of
the divine and Mosaic authorship

00:46:56.860 --> 00:46:59.984
of the Pentateuch,
the Torah, the first five books

00:46:59.984 --> 00:47:02.269
of Moses, were called into
question.

00:47:02.269 --> 00:47:06.102
The modern critical study of
the Bible begins really with

00:47:06.102 --> 00:47:09.729
Spinoza who in the early
seventeenth century suggested

00:47:09.729 --> 00:47:13.766
that the Bible should be studied
and examined like any book:

00:47:13.766 --> 00:47:17.804
without presuppositions about
its divine origin or any other

00:47:17.804 --> 00:47:21.909
dogmatic claims about its
composition or authorship.

00:47:21.909 --> 00:47:25.132
But it was a Catholic priest,
Richard Simon,

00:47:25.132 --> 00:47:28.878
who first argued that Moses
didn't write the Torah,

00:47:28.878 --> 00:47:33.000
and that it contained many
anachronisms and errors.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:35.770
Well we've run out of time,
but I'll pick up this

00:47:35.770 --> 00:47:39.118
fascinating story on Wednesday
and we'll learn a little bit

00:47:39.118 --> 00:47:42.869
more about critical ideas about
the composition of the Bible.

00:47:42.869 --> 00:47:45.970
Please be on the look out for
emails from section leaders with

00:47:45.970 --> 00:47:49.019
study guides for sections which
will be meeting this week;

00:47:49.019 --> 00:47:52.000
you'll have a lot of fun with
the creation stories.

